column16: ,"content":{"body":"\u003Ch4 style=\"padding-bottom: 8px; font-size: 16px;\"\u003EWhat is the Difference between a Graduate Job and a Graduate Program?\u003C\u002Fh4\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EWhen preparing to complete tertiary education
column17: , a career-minded student will plan for and seek out opportunities for graduate employment. While “\u003Cem\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003Egraduate jobs\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fem\u003E” and “\u003Cem\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003Egraduate programs\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fem\u003E” sound similar
column19: , purpose and size of organisation.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGraduate Jobs \u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGraduate jobs (or entry-level jobs)\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fem\u003E are open to and targeted towards university graduates. They occur in all industries
column20: , but since they are less structured than graduate programs
column21: , they are the main source of graduate employment in the small to medium business market. With these jobs
column22: , graduates are hired to perform a role at a full-time
column24:
, casual or contracting basis. Common titles for graduate jobs include:

  • Officer (as in “technical support officer” and “HR officer”)
  • Executive” (as in “sales executive”)
  • Representative (as in “customer service representative”)
  • Assistant
  • Administrator
  • Co-ordinator

Entry-level jobs provide a vast employment pool for university graduates
column25: , with a large variety of positions and options to choose from. They provide practical experience in a variety of skills
column26: , and the chance to build a professional reputation
column27: , as well as the chance to decide exactly what direction to take career-wise.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cspan style=\"text-decoration: underline;\" data-mce-mark=\"1\"\u003EApplying for a Graduate Job \u003C\u002Fspan\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EEntry-level employers assess candidates’ relevant knowledge and experience
column28: , seeking proof of their ability to perform the job. The first indicator of an applicant’s suitability is their CV
column29: , which should include their academic achievements
column30: , work experience and extra-curricular activities.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EWhen crafting your CV
column31: , it is important to not underestimate your abilities. Know your strengths
column32: , and match them to what the job requires. Usually a bachelor’s degree (with a Credit or Distinction average) is sufficient academic qualification for a graduate job.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EThink creatively about your experiences. For example
column33: , part-time work yields not only technical skills
column34: , but teaches desirable “soft skills” like collaboration
column35: , time-management and leadership. Think about how this applies to your desired job. That said; do not over-sell yourself. Stretching the truth in a CV may get you an interview
column36: , but the lies will be exposed when it comes to performing the job.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EAssuming your resume impresses the employer the next step will be an interview. Employees use interviews to gain a better understanding of their candidate’s knowledge and experience
column37: , critical thinking and creativity; and in particular their communication skills and organisational fit. Make sure you do some research into the company beforehand
column38: , and practice answering common interview questions so as to prepare yourself to speak with confidence. On the day; dress to impress (in business-attire). Answer all questions honestly. At the end you will be given the opportunity to ask the employer some questions yourself. Showing interest in the day-to-day running of the business
column39: , learning and development prospects of the job and future direction of the company helps to convince the employer that you have genuine enthusiasm for the job
column40: , and that you will fit in well with the organisation’s team.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGraduate Programs \u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EGraduate programs differ from graduate jobs in that they are structured
column41: , often providing some formal education (like a professional certification
column42: , or a diploma) as well as guided training in the organisation
column44: , and access to senior management. Graduate programs are usually full-time
column45: , and go for 12 months or more. They require significant investment in time and money
column46: , so only very large organisations (like big corporations and the government) can afford to offer them. Because of this substantial investment their entry requirements are very high
column47: , and only the best candidates will succeed in getting a position.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EA graduate program grooms candidates for a future in leadership and senior management. Since they are a boost on the corporate ladder
column48: , they are in high demand among graduates. However
column49: , failing to get a position in a graduate program does not discount someone from having a successful career since that ultimately depends on work quality
column53: , teamwork and networking.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EThe most in-demand graduate programs are with large corporations like the \u003Cspan style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"\u003EBig Four accounting firms\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E
column54: , Telstra and BHP Billiton. Jobs in \u003Ca title=\"Graduate Jobs in Accounting\" href=\"\u002Fgraduate-jobs\u002Faccounting\u002F\"\u003Eaccounting\u003C\u002Fa\u003E are the most sought-after
column56: , \u003Ca title=\"Information Technology Graduate Jobs and Programs\" href=\"\u002Fgraduate-jobs\u002Finformation-technology\u002F\"\u003EIT\u003C\u002Fa\u003E
column57: , \u003Ca title=\"Banking and Finance Graduate Jobs and Graduate Programs\" href=\"\u002Fgraduate-jobs\u002Fbanking-and-finance\u002F\"\u003Efinance\u003C\u002Fa\u003E
column58:
, policy making and engineering.

Features of Graduate Programs

  • Learning and Development
    Learning and Development is what sets a graduate program apart from an ordinary entry-level job. Organisations look to build upon and add to their employee’s existing skills base
column59: , and to that end they will conduct class-based learning and on-the-job training courses
column60: , both in the specifics of the work required and in “soft skills” like communication and team-building. They may host seminars and networking sessions
column61: , and bring in high-profile guest speakers to present on industry trends
column62: , motivation or leadership. Graduates will be guided through the learning and development program by a mentor or “buddy” as part of the program’s support system. After the graduate has completed the program
column63: , they will participate in ongoing organisation-wide professional development and training.\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\r\n\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cem\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERotational Programs\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fem\u003E \u003Cbr \u002F\u003EMany graduate programs in large organisations are rotational programs. Instead of spending a year in a single position
column64: , graduates are rotated around the various areas of the business every few months in order to gain a feel for the company and to gain experience in different types of work. Rotational programs are designed to help the graduate determine a position in which they will be able to add most value to the organisation
column65: , maximising both their enjoyment and productivity.\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\r\n\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cem\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPossible Relocation\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fem\u003E \u003Cbr \u002F\u003EOver one-third of graduate programs require the successful candidate to relocate to another city
column66: , region or state. This high percentage is in part due to gaps between demand and supply for graduate jobs – for example regionally-based employers (such as some mining companies and manufacturers) are unable to find satisfactory candidates from the local market to fill their vacancies
column67: , so must recruit from cities or interstate. Other organisations are based solely in one location but recruit from all over Australia to find the best candidates. These include the Federal Government and the Defence Force. Although relocation is a significant (and challenging) step for a graduate to make
column68:
, most employers ease the process by offering relocation assistance and support.

Applying for a Graduate Program

Although some graduate programs become available multiple times in a year
column69: , most organisations offering graduate programs open for applications in late February and early March
column70: , and close in April.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EImprove your chances of securing a graduate position by applying for multiple programs. This strategy will help you learn more about the kinds of skills and experience organisations seek. In 2013
column71: , the average successful candidate submitted applications to different companies. However
column72: , this average is indicative of a wide spread – while 28% of successful applicants made over ten applications
column73: , 19% were successful with only a single application.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003ERelevant tertiary qualification is important
column74: , with most successful applicants to graduate programs having studied commerce (including accounting
column79: , engineering or political science. Many large companies offer “generalist” recruitment programs
column80: , for which candidates from all disciplines are invited to apply
column81: , since a diverse knowledge-base is an asset.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003ECompanies offering graduate programs seek applicants with high academic achievement
column82: , and to that end candidates with scholarships and prizes are at an advantage. 54% of successful applicants in 2013 had a scholarship
column83: , prize or some kind of financial support from an organisation. In addition
column86: , dedication and initiative. Part-time work is a good indicator of these qualities
column87: , and is also a source of practical experience. 86% of graduates successfully hired to a graduate program had worked part-time at some point during university. Other extra-curricular activities common to successful candidates include volunteer work
column89: , relevant industry work experience and participation in student societies.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EApplication to a graduate program typically involves multiple steps
column90: , such as completing an \u003Cspan style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"\u003Eonline application\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E
column92: , a telephone interview and a face-to-face interview. At each point the applicant is screened before progressing to the next level. Although the application process is long and complex
column93: , the companies design the stages as much as possible to enable the candidate’s best qualities to shine. The tests and interviews will be challenging
column94: , but interactive and enjoyable. Shortlisted candidates may be invited to networking events to meet more of the company staff
column96: , and find out more of how the business works and whether the job is right for them.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EFinally
column97: , if a candidate passes every stage of the application process
column98: , they will be sent a formal offer by letter
column99: , including the full commencement details. Typically there will be a wait of two and a half months between the start of an application and receipt of an offer
